APRAJITA JAIN: Like
Rate Your Actors?

00:10:12.239 --> 00:10:13.610
ARJUN RAMPAL: The Crush App.

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:14.830
APRAJITA JAIN: No, but
tell me a little bit more

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:17.230
about how you moved from
modeling into acting,

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:19.270
and take us on that ramp.

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:21.010
ARJUN RAMPAL:
Yeah, so actually I

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:24.100
was going to be studying
finance and business.

00:10:24.100 --> 00:10:27.320
And I was really into sports.

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:28.630
I was running 400 meters.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:30.890
I ran state level.

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:32.950
And I really never
thought that I

00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:35.200
would get into the
entertainment business

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:37.630
because nobody
from my family was.

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:39.400
In fact, they're more
from the army side.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:41.680
Everybody wanted me
to join the army.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:46.620
My dad didn't join the army, but
both my dadaji and nanaji both

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:49.720
were from the army,
very decorated.

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:51.010
So I did not think--

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:54.550
I was the only
boy, so obviously I

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:57.130
didn't think I had
any score or chances.

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:58.800
I loved watching the movies.

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:00.390
From when I was
a kid, I remember

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:03.670
I used to go watch the
movies first day, first show,

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:06.950
and then dressed like those
heroes for a little while.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:12.295
But I didn't think that that
means that there's something--

00:11:12.295 --> 00:11:15.640
that it's going to be
pulling me towards acting.

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:17.200
So one day I was at a nightclub.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:19.090
And this designer saw me.

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:23.640
And he said, are you a model
and would you like to model?

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:25.690
So I thought he was
making a pass at me.

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:26.710
And I was like, no, sir.

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:27.340
No.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:30.249
No interest in modeling.

00:11:30.249 --> 00:11:32.290
But actually it turned
out to be a family friend.

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:35.740
His name was Rohit Bal, who is
now one of my closest friends.

00:11:35.740 --> 00:11:38.750
And from there, I was
an economic student,

00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:41.480
and economically it
made a lot of sense

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:46.700
to me that [INAUDIBLE] to go and
stand on or walk on the ramp,

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:48.720
or wear some very nice clothes.

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:51.170
It pays you a lot
more than I would

00:11:51.170 --> 00:11:55.040
be getting paid by any bank
or any financial institute

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:59.990
that I'd be working for,
unless of course I owned it.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:03.050
So from there-- and
I really enjoyed it.

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:04.700
From there, it kind of grew--

00:12:04.700 --> 00:12:06.380
one thing grew into another.

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:10.550
I worked with wonderful people,
like Ashok Mehta, Skehar Kapur,

00:12:10.550 --> 00:12:13.730
through my modeling
career, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:17.780
who kind of insisted
that I get into acting

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:19.280
and to the movie business.

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:20.790
Then I came to New York.

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:24.200
I wanted to study
filmmaking here

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:26.870
and enrolled in NYU film school.

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:28.700
But by the time
I went back home,

00:12:28.700 --> 00:12:32.060
Ashok Mehta I had this film
called "Moksha," which I did.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:36.020
And once I bit that
Apple, like Adam bit his,

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:39.750
I was completely taken
in into this industry.

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:42.000
And I'm really glad
that that happened.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.800
So a lot of credit to Ashok-ji,
may his soul rest in peace.

00:12:45.800 --> 00:12:47.260
He's not with us anymore.

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:49.460
But truly, from
there, Rajiv Rai,

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:51.480
all these people in the
beginning who really,

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.600
really helped me
from being a nobody

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:54.819
to reach wherever I reach.

00:12:54.819 --> 00:12:57.110
APRAJITA JAIN: We are very
grateful to all these people

00:12:57.110 --> 00:12:58.943
too, because otherwise
we wouldn't know you.

00:12:58.943 --> 00:13:00.740
