00:16:42.590 --> 00:16:43.110
OK.

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:45.440
But what's the resemblance?

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:47.390
I mean, how do we
even look alike?

00:16:47.390 --> 00:16:50.480
Because if you see Arun
Gawli, and please Google him,

00:16:50.480 --> 00:16:52.130
you will know--

00:16:52.130 --> 00:16:56.480
so once you know, it's
completely different,

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:58.480
the way we look.

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:00.380
But I started
reading up about him.

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:03.740
And I found his life
extremely intriguing.

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:08.720
And I found him a very reluctant
kind of a gangster, which

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.125
was very, very different.

00:17:10.125 --> 00:17:12.500
It wasn't the gangster who
was going to be walking around

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:14.270
with all guns blazing.

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:16.790
He was a guy who used his mind.

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:21.470
He was a guy who went
through a journey, which--

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:24.040
from gangster, turned
into a politician,

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:25.579
was called the Robin Hood.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:27.500
And what was the most
amazing part of it

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:30.860
was that people call him Daddy.

00:17:30.860 --> 00:17:33.200
They don't call him by--
they don't call him Don.

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:36.300
They don't call him, you know--

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:39.020
you know, whatever,
other terms that you

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:41.630
use for gangsters in India.

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:42.500
They call him Daddy.

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:44.230
Why would somebody
call him Daddy?

00:17:44.230 --> 00:17:45.680
Because he actually went
out there and looked

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:46.700
after a lot of people.

00:17:46.700 --> 00:17:49.332
APRAJITA JAIN: Interesting.

00:17:49.332 --> 00:17:50.790
ARJUN RAMPAL: But
at the same time,

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:55.266
we wanted not to make this film
a very propaganda kind of film.

00:17:55.266 --> 00:17:57.140
But I was still not
impressed with the script

00:17:57.140 --> 00:17:58.740
that came to me earlier.

00:17:58.740 --> 00:18:00.800
So I kept rejecting
it, rejecting it,

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:02.690
but I got very upset with it.

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:05.420
And in that process
of my obsession,

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:09.860
I locked myself in a hotel
room for three months,

00:18:09.860 --> 00:18:12.800
and I started
writing this story.

00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:16.130
And suddenly the story
came about and got life.

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:19.730
And then I gave it to one
of my biggest critics,

00:18:19.730 --> 00:18:23.660
who is the director
of this film, whose

00:18:23.660 --> 00:18:25.490
name is Ashim Ahluwalia.

00:18:25.490 --> 00:18:27.410
And he's a really, really
fantastic director.

00:18:27.410 --> 00:18:30.550
He'd made this film called "Miss
Lovely," which did really well

00:18:30.550 --> 00:18:33.690
in the Cannes,
indie film circuit.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:36.890
He's extremely great
with detailing.

00:18:36.890 --> 00:18:40.850
And everybody's asked him to
make a movie, and he said no.

00:18:40.850 --> 00:18:42.260
So I gave him the script.

00:18:42.260 --> 00:18:45.020
I said, he's going to rip it
apart because I don't know

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:47.000
if he'll-- you know?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:48.612
And he read the script.

00:18:48.612 --> 00:18:49.820
And he said, dude, I love it.

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:50.361
I'm doing it.

00:18:50.361 --> 00:18:52.670
I said, but Ashim, I
don't want you to do it.

00:18:52.670 --> 00:18:54.980
I was just asking you
to read the script.

00:18:54.980 --> 00:18:56.585
I don't want you to direct it.

00:18:56.585 --> 00:18:57.800
But he said, no, dude.

00:18:57.800 --> 00:18:58.730
I'm doing the script.

00:18:58.730 --> 00:18:59.340
I love it.

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:00.820
But we're going to tweak it.

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:02.990
So Ashim and me kind of
co-wrote it after that.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:04.670
It was a long process.

00:19:04.670 --> 00:19:06.950
Then we got the permissions
from the family.

00:19:06.950 --> 00:19:10.350
We did a tremendous
amount of research.

00:19:10.350 --> 00:19:10.940
See?

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:12.860
He took me to all
these crazy locations,

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:17.750
like you're seeing,
which are rat infested.

00:19:17.750 --> 00:19:19.550
And I'll make a confession here.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:22.250
I have-- I hate rats, OK?

00:19:22.250 --> 00:19:25.920
I can fight a tiger, but if
you put a rat in front of me,

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:28.700
I will run away from that room.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:30.920
So he's got this really
great aesthetic sense.

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:32.930
This is all his framing.

00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:36.860
So it's-- and to create
that world, we needed Ashim.

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:39.141
And then we went out
there and we made it.

00:19:39.141 --> 00:19:41.390
APRAJITA JAIN: And how was
Arun Gawli himself involved

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:41.960
in that process?

00:19:41.960 --> 00:19:43.000
Did you meet him a lot?

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.264
Did you ask him about his
past life and what he did?

00:19:46.264 --> 00:19:47.180
ARJUN RAMPAL: So, yes.

00:19:47.180 --> 00:19:50.820
I did have the opportunity
to meet him a couple of times

00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:53.090
when he came out on parole.

00:19:53.090 --> 00:19:55.760
And of course met a
lot with the people

00:19:55.760 --> 00:20:00.470
who are involved with
him, like the shooters,

00:20:00.470 --> 00:20:05.930
the people who were part
of his gang at that time.

00:20:05.930 --> 00:20:09.950
He's in prison now, so he
does come out on parole.

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:12.650
And he's a very, very--
what was really amazing

00:20:12.650 --> 00:20:15.710
about him was that he is
not at all intimidating.

00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:18.062
He is actually very humble.

00:20:18.062 --> 00:20:19.437
APRAJITA JAIN:
He's Daddy, right?

00:20:19.437 --> 00:20:20.720
ARJUN RAMPAL: Yeah.

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:26.230
And what's really amazing
about him is that--

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:28.580
they're very gentle.

00:20:28.580 --> 00:20:30.100
And they have so many--

00:20:30.100 --> 00:20:32.690
they're so well
mannered, you know?

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:36.050
They speak with a lot of
respect, what you call tehzeeb.

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.840
You know, they have a
lot of good manners.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:40.700
They speak really, really well.

00:20:40.700 --> 00:20:43.020
They're not-- they
don't raise their voice.

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:45.020
And it was amazing.

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:48.230
It was amazing to see that,
get that body language.

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:51.530
And one day we were
shooting in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:51.530 --> 00:20:54.740
And he was also
out at that time,

00:20:54.740 --> 00:20:56.540
so he was watching
a bit of the shoot.

00:20:56.540 --> 00:21:00.380
So he was sitting like this
and I was sitting here,

00:21:00.380 --> 00:21:03.130
and then he went away somewhere.

00:21:03.130 --> 00:21:04.400
And it was really strange.

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:06.320
One of his relatives came out--

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:08.690
and I was dressed
like this, OK--

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:11.580
and came out and
touched my feet.

00:21:11.580 --> 00:21:13.200
They thought it was--

00:21:13.200 --> 00:21:15.320
so that was, I think,
the biggest compliment

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:17.030
that happened in [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:17.030 --> 00:21:18.611
And so yeah.

00:21:18.611 --> 00:21:20.360
There have been a lot
of great experiences

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:21.693
that have happened through here.

00:21:21.693 --> 00:21:23.840
It's not been an easy
film to make, because we

00:21:23.840 --> 00:21:25.880
wanted to keep it realistic.

00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:28.310
We wanted not it
to be a propaganda

00:21:28.310 --> 00:21:33.290
film, where you are
kind of glamorizing

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:35.150
a life of a gangster.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:39.230
But we wanted to keep
it true to what it was.

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:42.830
We also believe that
there is a story out there

00:21:42.830 --> 00:21:47.510
where somebody goes to jail,
serves his time, you know,

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:50.690
comes out, and we send
the person to jail

00:21:50.690 --> 00:21:54.600
really to want that
person to reform.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:57.390
But do we really
honestly as a society

00:21:57.390 --> 00:21:59.490
give that person
a second chance?

00:21:59.490 --> 00:22:03.162
That is something also you get
to explore through the film.

00:22:03.162 --> 00:22:04.530
APRAJITA JAIN: Fantastic.

00:22:04.530 --> 00:22:07.290
Well, you have really whet
our appetite about this movie,

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:08.850
about-- you talked
so much about it.

